--> Accounting Engine Logic

1) Scenario 1: You sell вӮ№10,000 worth of goods to a customer in the same state, 18% GST.
Step 1 вҖ” Sales Module receives the request
The user clicks "Create Invoice" on the frontend. The API receives: customer ID, list of items with quantities and prices.
Step 2 вҖ” Sales Module calls GST Calculator
It sends the item's HSN code, the amount (вӮ№10,000), your state (MH), and the customer's state (MH). GST Calculator sees same state, returns:
CGST: вӮ№900
SGST: вӮ№900
IGST: вӮ№0
Total: вӮ№11,800
Step 3 вҖ” Sales Module calls Inventory Service
It says "reduce 5 units of Item X from Warehouse A." Inventory checks if stock is available, reduces it, records the movement.
Step 4 вҖ” Sales Module builds the accounting entries
This is the key part. The Sales Module creates an array:
entries = [
  { account: "Accounts Receivable (Customer)",  debit: 11800,  credit: 0     },
  { account: "Sales Revenue",                   debit: 0,      credit: 10000 },
  { account: "CGST Payable",                    debit: 0,      credit: 900   },
  { account: "SGST Payable",                    debit: 0,      credit: 900   },
]
Step 5 вҖ” Sales Module sends this array to Accounting Engine
The Sales Module does NOT save these entries itself. It calls accountingEngine.postVoucher(entries).
Step 6 вҖ” Accounting Engine validates
It adds up all debits: 11800. It adds up all credits: 10000 + 900 + 900 = 11800. Are they equal? Yes. Proceed.
Step 7 вҖ” Accounting Engine saves
Inside a single database transaction (prisma.$transaction), it creates the voucher header and all four ledger entries. If any one fails, all roll back. Nothing is half-saved.

2) Scenario 2: You BUY goods from a supplier

Purchase Module calls вҶ’ GST Calculator
Purchase Module calls вҶ’ Inventory Service
Purchase Module calls вҶ’ Accounting Engine

Step 1 вҖ” Purchase Module receives the request. User clicks "Record Purchase Invoice." API receives supplier ID, list of items, quantities, prices.
Step 2 вҖ” Purchase Module calls GST Calculator. Sends HSN code, amount вӮ№50,000, your state (MH), supplier's state (GJ). Different states, so GST Calculator returns IGST вӮ№9,000.
Step 3 вҖ” Purchase Module calls Inventory Service. It says "add 100 units of Item Y to Warehouse A." Inventory increases the stock, records the movement.
Step 4 вҖ” Purchase Module builds the entries.
entries = [
  { account: "Purchase Account",            debit: 50000,  credit: 0     },
  { account: "IGST Input Credit",           debit: 9000,   credit: 0     },
  { account: "Accounts Payable (Supplier)", debit: 0,      credit: 59000 },
]
Step 5 вҖ” Purchase Module sends to Accounting Engine. Same postVoucher(entries) call.
Step 6 вҖ” Engine validates. Debits: 50000 + 9000 = 59000. Credits: 59000. Equal? Yes.
Step 7 вҖ” Engine saves atomically.


3) Scenario 3:  You PAY the supplier


Step 1 вҖ” User clicks "Pay Supplier." 
         API receives: supplier ID, amount вӮ№59,000, bank account.

Step 3 вҖ” Build entries:
entries = [
  { account: "Accounts Payable (Supplier)",  debit: 59000,  credit: 0     },
  { account: "Bank Account",                 debit: 0,      credit: 59000 },
]

Step 4 вҖ” Send to Accounting Engine.

Step 5 вҖ” Engine validates. Debit: 59000. Credit: 59000. Equal? Yes.

Step 6 вҖ” Engine saves.


4) Scenario 4:  Business Expense (Internet Bill with GST)


Step 1 вҖ” User clicks "Record Expense." 
         API receives: expense head (Internet), amount вӮ№5,000, 
         HSN/SAC code, vendor state.

Step 2 вҖ” Expense Module calls GST Calculator.
         Sends: amount вӮ№5,000, SAC code, your state (MH), 
         vendor state (MH). Same state вҶ’ returns:
         CGST: вӮ№450, SGST: вӮ№450

Step 3 вҖ” Expense Module builds entries:
entries = [
  { account: "Internet Expense",   debit: 5000, credit: 0    },
  { account: "CGST Input Credit",  debit: 450,  credit: 0    },
  { account: "SGST Input Credit",  debit: 450,  credit: 0    },
  { account: "Bank Account",       debit: 0,    credit: 5900 },
]

Step 4 вҖ” Sends to Accounting Engine.

Step 5 вҖ” Engine validates. Debit: 5900. Credit: 5900. Yes.

Step 6 вҖ” Engine saves atomically.


5) Scenario 5: Sales RETURN

Step 1 вҖ” User clicks "Sales Return." 
         API receives: original invoice ID, items being returned 
         with quantities, reason for return.

Step 2 вҖ” Sales Module calls GST Calculator.
         Sends: return amount вӮ№2,000, HSN code, same state.
         Returns: CGST вӮ№180, SGST вӮ№180.

Step 3 вҖ” Sales Module calls Inventory Service.
         "Add back 5 units of Item X to Warehouse A."
         Stock increases.

Step 4 вҖ” Sales Module builds entries:
entries = [
  { account: "Sales Return",          debit: 2000, credit: 0    },
  { account: "CGST Payable",          debit: 180,  credit: 0    },
  { account: "SGST Payable",          debit: 180,  credit: 0    },
  { account: "Accounts Receivable",   debit: 0,    credit: 2360 },
]

Step 5 вҖ” Sends to Accounting Engine.

Step 6 вҖ” Engine validates. Debit: 2360. Credit: 2360. Yes.

Step 7 вҖ” Engine saves atomically.


6) Scenario 6: Customer Pays


Step 1 вҖ” User clicks "Record Payment."
         API receives: customer ID, amount вӮ№11,800, 
         bank account, invoice reference.

Step 2 вҖ” No GST. No Inventory. Just money moving.

Step 3 вҖ” Build entries:
entries = [
  { account: "Bank Account",           debit: 11800, credit: 0     },
  { account: "Accounts Receivable",    debit: 0,     credit: 11800 },
]

Step 4 вҖ” Send to Accounting Engine.

Step 5 вҖ” Engine validates. Debit: 11800. Credit: 11800. Yes.

Step 6 вҖ” Engine saves.



Transaction Cheat Sheet:
Sales Invoice      вҶ’ GST + Inventory (stock DOWN) + Accounting Engine
Purchase Invoice   вҶ’ GST + Inventory (stock UP) + Accounting Engine
Customer Payment   вҶ’ Accounting Engine ONLY
Supplier Payment   вҶ’ Accounting Engine ONLY
Business Expense   вҶ’ GST + Accounting Engine (no inventory)
Sales Return       вҶ’ GST + Inventory (stock UP) + Accounting Engine
Purchase Return    вҶ’ GST + Inventory (stock DOWN) + Accounting Engine


The Accounting Engine is intentionally dumb. It does not know what a sale or purchase is. It receives entries, 
validates the balance, and saves. All business intelligence lives in the calling module.